The paper deals with mechanism design and auction theory, which are core topics in computer science and economics. The use of LP relaxations and rounding schemes suggests a focus on optimization and algorithms, which are common in the cs.GT (game theory) and cs.DS (data structures and algorithms) sub-categories. The paper also deals with Bayesian incentive compatibility, which is a key concept in artificial intelligence and machine learning, making cs.AI a likely sub-category. The use of hazard rate conditions and product distributions suggests a focus on probability theory and information theory, which are relevant to the cs.EC (economics and computation) and cs.IT (information theory) sub-categories.
